<br>
A brief tutorial, skip if you wish... but note the many complete sentences <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
III. GRAMMAR<br>
<br>
IIIa. PLURALIZATION<br>
<br>
Withstanding irregular forms, a plural is completed by &quot;en&quot; if it ends in a consonant or &quot;n&quot; if it ends in a vowel.<br>
<br>
Singular Plural <br>
Jabbress<br>
{Mistress} <br>
 Jabbressen<br>
{Mistresses} <br>
 <br>
Velve {Blade} <br>
 Velven {Blades} <br>
<br>
 <br>
IIIb. POSSESSIVE CASE<br>
<br>
Coincidentally, the possessive case in the Drow language is very similar to the Common Tongue used by most races. The possessive case is completed with &quot;'s&quot; except if the word ends in &quot;s&quot; where upon &quot;'&quot; is added.<br>
<br>
Sarn lil velg'larn's inthen <br>
 {Beware the assassin's schemes} <br>
 <br>
Nindil zhah lil Valsharess' elgluth <br>
 {That is the Valsharess' whip} <br>
 <br>
<br>
IIIc. VERBS<br>
<br>
A verb has different forms depending on its number (singular or plural); person (first, second, third); voice (active, passive); tense (present, past, future, present perfect, past perfect, future perfect); and mood (indicative, imperative, subjunctive).<br>
<br>
NUMBER: Withstanding irregular verbs, the singular form is completed with &quot;ar&quot;.<br>
<br>
Singular Plural <br>
Lil sargtlin elggar<br>
{The warrior kills} <br>
 Lil sargtlinen elgg<br>
{The warriors kill} <br>
 <br>
Uss jaluk elar<br>
{One male dies} <br>
 Draa jaluken el<br>
{Two males die} <br>
 <br>
PERSON: Verbs usually have a different form only in the third person singular of the present tense. Withstanding irregular verbs, the third person singular of the present tense is completed with &quot;e&quot;. <br>
<br>
Usstan belbau<br>
{I give} <br>
 Dos belbau<br>
{You give} <br>
 Uk belbaue<br>
{He gives} <br>
 <br>
Usstan luth<br>
{I cast} <br>
 Dos luth<br>
{You cast} <br>
 Il luthe<br>
{She casts} <br>
 <br>
<br>
VOICE: A passive verb is a combination of a &quot;be&quot; verb and a past participle.<br>
<br>
Active L'Yathrin harventhe ukt karliik<br>
{The Yathrin severs his head} <br>
 <br>
Passive Ukt karliik zhahus harventhus a'lil Yathrin<br>
{Hishead was severed by the Yathrin} <br>
 <br>
<br>
TENSE: Withstanding irregular verbs, the past tense is completed with &quot;us&quot;.<br>
<br>
  Active Voice Passive Voice <br>
Present Tense Uk phlithe<br>
{He hates} <br>
 Uk zhah phlithus<br>
{He is hated} <br>
 <br>
Past Tense Usstan phlithus<br>
{I hated} <br>
 Usstan zhahus phlithus<br>
{I was hated} <br>
 <br>
Future Tense Dos orn phlith<br>
{You will hate} <br>
 Dos orn tlu phlithus<br>
{You will be hated} <br>
 <br>
Present Perfect Dos inbal phlithus<br>
{You have hated} <br>
 Dos inbal tlus phlithus<br>
{You have been hated} <br>
 <br>
Past Perfect Il inbalus phlithus<br>
{She had hated} <br>
 Il inbalus tlus phlithus<br>
{She had been hated} <br>
 <br>
Future Perfect Usstan zhal inbal phlithus<br>
{I shall have hated} <br>
 Usstan zhal inbal tlus phlithus<br>
{I shall have been hated} <br>
 <br>
<br>
MOOD: The mood of the verb indicates the tone in which the statement is made. The common &quot;-ing&quot; ending found in many verbs of the indicative mood is completed with &quot;-in&quot;. There are no other endings for the imperative or subjunctive moods.<br>
<br>
Indicative <br>
 Udos phuul raldarin l'waess da'fol rivvin.<br>
{We are stripping the skin from some humans} <br>
 <br>
<br>
IIId. ADJECTIVES<br>
<br>
Adjectives have three forms: positive, comparative, and superlative. Withstanding irregular forms, the comparative form is completed with &quot;ur&quot; while the superlative is completed with &quot;url&quot;. The common &quot;-ful&quot;suffix for many adjectives is indicated by &quot;'urn&quot;. <br>
<br>
Positive Comparative Superlative <br>
Olath<br>
{Dark} <br>
 Olathur<br>
{Darker} <br>
 Olathurl<br>
{Darkest} <br>
 <br>
Ssin'urn<br>
{Beautiful} <br>
 Mzild ssin'urn<br>
{More beautiful} <br>
 Mzilst ssin'urn<br>
{Most beautiful} <br>
 <br>
IIIe. ADVERBS<br>
<br>
Adverbs, like adjectives, have three forms: positive, comparative, and superlative. Withstanding irregular forms, the comparative form is completed with &quot;ur&quot; while the superlative is completed with &quot;url&quot;. The common &quot;-ly&quot; suffix for many adverbs is indicated by &quot;ne&quot; (or &quot;e&quot; if ending in &quot;n&quot;).<br>
<br>
<br>
__________________________<br>
<br>
This ends the brief tutorial.... Drow 101 Further resources are available if you wish to develop a real understanding of the complete language.<br>
<br>
As you can see, complete sentances are quite easy to form and if you would like to brows just one dictionary you will find the actual vocabulary to be quite extensive.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://php.iupui.edu/~asimmon/drow.html#verbs">php.iupui.edu/~asimmon/drow.html#verbs</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Frankly, the reason you do not hear Tier'dal use more of the language instead of just pieces thrown in for flavor is precicely because most people wouldnt understand at all. Not because it isnt possible. As it is, most players only use words that in context most people can grasp. However it is indeed sad that there does seem to be a major decline in school studies regarding reading comprehension 101.<br>
<br>
If you find this arrogant... well, so be it. It also happens to be quite fun.<br>
<br>
Aluve dos jal, bel'la dos! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/unikirose.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nikirose</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://NoirDaila.homestead.com/files/Laney/america.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/13/02 6:04:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2521.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.extremezone.com/~medieval/buttons/bloodsword.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Abbils... above jal else...Xathari</span><hr size=1> Incomplete or Ancient?<br>
<br>
Think of it as an Ancient Dialect.  Grasping at the concept that Tier'dal are their own race and not the offshoot another race some Tier'dal desire their uniqueness (sp).  Thereforw we use use the phrases that are common as our link to our history.  Vendui (Hello) Aluve (good bye) Vendaust (see you later)  etc.  Abbil (friend or comrade).<br>
<br>
Some Tier'dal despise the language and say mean or hurtful things to those that choose to use it.  NO problem.  Different families have differnet beliefs in history and proper use of language.<br>
<br>
The most common phrases heard among Norrath are the ancient proverbs, titles of respect, curses against the enemy, blessings for the battle about to come.  Tradition really.<br>
<br>
In America a lot of people don't speak other languages, but depending on what part of the country you live in you may know some specific phrases.  Hola, como estas?  (hi how are you).  Bonjour, comment allez vous?  (Hi how are you) Is it wrong for us to know these limited phrases or even to use them?  No, it just makes the conversation a bit more colorful.<br>
<br>
Do not disrespect those choosing to speak &quot;drow&quot;.  If you don't understand or as  Tier'dal choose not to use it, be polite.  A simple &quot;I don't speak that language&quot; or &quot;Again in common please&quot;  will go much farther than a rude comment about how &quot;stupid&quot; one is for trying to add flavor to an otherwise monotonous language of &quot;Plz Sow Dood?&quot;  or &quot;k thx&quot;.<br>
<br>
Just some boring rambling observations.<br>
<br>
Laney<br>
